You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice intermittently experiences CPU spikes to 100% and becomes unresponsive. Thread dumps indicate multiple worker threads are permanently stuck in `RUNNABLE` state inside the `put` method of a custom, non-blocking open-addressing hash map. Below is the simplified code snippet:

java
public class CustomConcurrentMap<K, V> {
    private static class Entry<K, V> {
        final K key;
        volatile V value;
        Entry(K key, V value) { this.key = key; this.value = value; }
    }
    private final AtomicReferenceArray<Entry<K, V>> table = new AtomicReferenceArray<>(1024);

    public void put(K key, V value) {
        int h = Math.abs(key.hashCode());
        int idx = h % table.length();
        while (true) {
            Entry<K, V> current = table.get(idx);
            if (current == null) {
                if (table.compareAndSet(idx, null, new Entry<>(key, value))) {
                    return;
                }
            } else if (current.key.equals(key)) {
                current.value = value;
                return;
            }
            idx = (idx + 1) % table.length();
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where an in-memory caching service experiences severe `OutOfMemoryError` (OOM) errors under high write load. The service implements a custom cache designed to keep heavy metadata objects using `SoftReference` values, allowing the JVM to reclaim them when heap pressure is high. The underlying storage is a `ConcurrentHashMap`:

java
public class CustomSoftCache<K, V> {
    private final Map<K, SoftReference<V>> cache = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
    private final ReferenceQueue<V> queue = new ReferenceQueue<>();
    // Background thread polls 'queue' to clean up stale entries from the 'cache' map
}

Even under high GC activity, the JVM crashes with an OOM before reclaiming memory.

You are debugging a production issue where a Spring-managed transactional service is experiencing silent data loss. The application uses a custom in-memory doubly-linked list wrapper called `PendingTaskQueue` to buffer outgoing tasks. This custom collection is injected as a bean into a `@Service` component:

java
@Service
public class TaskProcessor {
    @Autowired
    private PendingTaskQueue taskQueue;

    @Transactional
    public void processBatch() {
        Task task = taskQueue.poll();
        if (task != null) {
            executeAndPersist(task); // Interacts with database
        }
    }
}

During database connection drops, Spring successfully rolls back the transaction, but the tasks that were polled from `taskQueue` are lost forever.
